The doctrine ol atoms, as being the original elements oi all things, is silly and untenable; but even granting it to be true. and so supposing the gods to have arisen lrom atoms, their immortality would be in contradiction with it (65-68). But in order to be able to maintain this immortality Epicurus takes his usual course when he wishes to escape the consequences os his own principles3 he flies to other arbitrary and inconceivable propositions. The gods, says he, are not corporea, but only quasi corporea! beings.¹ But this quasi corporeality is a word devoid oi sense, con- veying no idea even to Epicurus and his disciples (69-75). But let this pass, if we will. the case is no better for the assertion that the gods have human forms. The reasons given by the Epicureans in support ol this are next reiuted one after another3 and especially the assertion, that no person can imagine the gods* under any other form, is rejected as practically salse, since many represent them under the figures os beasts (76-82). But it is quite unworthy oi a philosopher to appeal to representations oi that sort.
